>What makes you say that?

Maybe I misremember, but I thought you were firmly on the side of the "platonists"
in those days when we were having our "platonist/pragmatist" discussions.

>> Yes, if you take the view that clarity is
>> a function of Players' actual perception and not just of the words themselves,
>> Macross is correct.  What I am waiting to hear is a convincing argument that
>> the wording of the SA Rule supports one interpretation over the other.

>In my opinion, an indication by itself is neither clear or unclear.  It is
>merely an indication.  Clarity is in the eye of the beholder.  If the
>clarity doesn't lie there, then where does it lie?    If I indicate in
>Swahili that I want to submit a proposal, is that clear if no one in the
>game knows the tongue but me (I don't but this is just hypothetical)?  Even
>the acrostic example was clear once it was pointed out.  Of course before it
>was pointed out, it is was unclear.  The entire context of the indication
>must be considered.

It is this last sentence where you lose me.  If you said "the entire context
*should* be considered",  then we would not be that far apart in our
positions - I 'm just searching for a justification as to how this particular
Rule supports considering the entire context.  But when you say "the entire
context *must* be considered", then I have trouble, because it seems
you are saying that it needs no justification, that it is self-evident in the
definition of "clear".

>Webster's Online Dictionary defines clear thusly:
<snip>
>     3 a : easily heard b : easily visible : PLAIN c : free from obscurity or
>     ambiguity : easily understood : UNMISTAKABLE
<snip>
>I would say that 3a, 3b, 4b, 6d are just about what I think of when I think
>of a clear indication.  I also think that this definition is in the best
>interests of the game.  If a reasonable person, or perhaps the 'average'
>person, would find the indication clear in the context in which it was
>presented then it is clear.  Otherwise it is not.

>In my opinion, Steve's indication was not clear.  It does not meet
>definition 6d above in that it is not free from obstruction.

I don't think the definition helps that much.  What you have just shown,
IMO, is that given a comprehensive list of possibilities for the definition
of a word, you can pick and choose what you need from it to
support any reasonable interpretation.  It is clear 8) from the above
list, that any interpretation of "clear" does not have to meet
*all* of the above possibilities.  You choose 6d, "free from obstruction",
to support your contention that the entire context must be used.
Steve uses only 3c, "easily understood", to support eir contention
that the imbedded indication was "clear".  Both choices are
reasonable, but there is still nothing there to tell us which one
is the more correct one.

>I honestly don't want to support this conclusion.  I think it will remove
>many nice scamming opportunities but I feel that it is the best
>interpretation.

I honestly am sympathetic to your interpretation, but it still seems more
like a coin toss to me.

--Crito

