macross wrote:

>It is not necessary for a player to actually see the indication for it to be
>clear.  Imagine if you will:

>A child is given a pain reliever for a headache, suffers an overdose and
>dies (god forbid).  The drug company points out that although the parents
>didn't read the bottle it clearly indicates only one tablet should be given
>to children of that age.  You, as judge, read the label and see that an
>indication to that effect is, in fact, there.  Also the wording of the
>indication is very plain and straightforward, in fact you might call it
>clear.  However, since it isn't in the dosage section, but is in fact buried
>in a bunch of flowery text about how the product is made only from the most
>natural of plants grown in the Andes mountains, farmed by native workers who
>have used the herb for 10 generations, blah, blah, blah, you decide that the
>indication was far from clear in any way that matters and the drug company
>is guilty of gross negligence.

>Now, do you care to argue with the grieving parents that it was a clear
>indication?  Or do you recognize that there is more to a clear indication
>than clear wording?

/melodrama on

You have chosen an example which causes our very humanity to cry out
for your interpretation of "clear".  Who among us (besides lawyers) could
be so heartless as to deny that the drug company bore a responsibility not
only to make the wording clear but also to make sure the words would be
easily perceived?

/melodrama off

But this is not such a life and death situation.  Does "indication" in R1483
refer only to the words themselves or to the entire message in which the
words are written?  The problem here is that you could easily substitute
the words "clear wording" for "the clear indication" into R1483.  So while
I recognize that there *can* be more to a clear indication than clear
wording, I'm still not convinced that there is more to it in this particular
case.

--Crito

