A short time ago I had been about to post with precisely the above 
remark of Michael's - then hit the 'cancel' button when precisely the 
above objection occurred to me. ;)

Still and all, I don't think we can avoid the conclusion that the 
fact of embedding a communication with potential legal significance 
within a larger volume of text of no legal significant should have 
some bearing on our interpretation of "clear indication" in such a 
context. Something along those lines - if Steve's post had in fact 
been three email messages - one with the first 'spam' part, a second 
with the Proposals, a third one with the rest of the spam - the 
Proposals would have stood out more clearly. In particular, if Steve 
had used a different Subject: header for the second message, that 
particular message would have been read with essentially the same 
attention as other agora-business messages. And of course anyone 
opening the second message would immediately have spotted the legal 
significance of its contents, rather than delete the message out of 
hand as would have been the case for the other two, categorized as 
'spam' after only a single glance at the first dozen or so lines.

So, these characteristics of a single mail message - its Subject 
line, its overall length, and the impression of a subject matter that 
the first few lines convey - are in fact as much part of the 
communication as "the words themselves" (as Crito refers to the part 
of Steve's message that, if they'd stood on their own, would have 
been a 'clear indication'), in that their modification will elicit 
different behaviours on the part of the recipient of the entire  
communication - which includes "the words themselves".

Given the case of a single message which contained, say, 10 Calls For 
Judgement, one Nomination, and at the end some Proposal worded 
similarly to Steve's, our judgement on whether this constituted a 
'clear indication' would have to take into account the fact that the 
first parts of the message were themselves clearly intended to have 
legal significance; and if the Subject line was '10 CFJs, a   
Nomination, and a Proposal' the case would be clear-cut.

Hey, and we still haven't gotten around to the charges of 
Impersonation and/or Misrepresentation yet. ;)


