Good heavens no!

> It is this last sentence where you lose me.  If you said "the
> entire context
> *should* be considered",  then we would not be that far apart in our
> positions - I 'm just searching for a justification as to how
> this particular
> Rule supports considering the entire context.  But when you say
> "the entire
> context *must* be considered", then I have trouble, because it seems
> you are saying that it needs no justification, that it is
> self-evident in the
> definition of "clear".
>

If it is to be clear in all senses of the word that can reasonably be
applied then, in my opinion, the entire context must be considered.  How
else can we determine if it is free from obstruction.

> >Webster's Online Dictionary defines clear thusly:
> <snip>
> >     3 a : easily heard b : easily visible : PLAIN c : free from
> obscurity or
> >     ambiguity : easily understood : UNMISTAKABLE
> <snip>
> >I would say that 3a, 3b, 4b, 6d are just about what I think of
> when I think
> >of a clear indication.  I also think that this definition is in the best
> >interests of the game.  If a reasonable person, or perhaps the 'average'
> >person, would find the indication clear in the context in which it was
> >presented then it is clear.  Otherwise it is not.
>
> >In my opinion, Steve's indication was not clear.  It does not meet
> >definition 6d above in that it is not free from obstruction.
>
> I don't think the definition helps that much.  What you have just shown,
> IMO, is that given a comprehensive list of possibilities for the
> definition
> of a word, you can pick and choose what you need from it to
> support any reasonable interpretation.
>It is clear 8) from the above
> list, that any interpretation of "clear" does not have to meet
> *all* of the above possibilities.  You choose 6d, "free from obstruction",
> to support your contention that the entire context must be used.
> Steve uses only 3c, "easily understood", to support eir contention
> that the imbedded indication was "clear".  Both choices are
> reasonable, but there is still nothing there to tell us which one
> is the more correct one.

And we need nothing to tell us that at all.  I require it to meet all
definitions that could reasonably and consistently be applied to the word in
the context of the rule.  I merely said that those definitions were what *I*
think of when I think of a clear indication.  But what I think is
irrelevant.  If we can consistently require all of these definitions then we
are required by the rule to do so as it doesn't specify any particular sense
of the word.  An indication that is "easily understood" is not necessarily
"free from obstruction" but can be both and in the absence of any compelling
reason not to believe the rule requires both, we must interpret it as
requiring both.

>
> >I honestly don't want to support this conclusion.  I think it will remove
> >many nice scamming opportunities but I feel that it is the best
> >interpretation.
>
> I honestly am sympathetic to your interpretation, but it still seems more
> like a coin toss to me.
>

I don't understand this.  Why do you feel that it's an either-or situation?
I feel it requires the indication to be clear in all reasonable senses of
the word.  I'm not arguing against Steve's definition so much as I'm saying
"Yes, and this too."

-Macross


