> But this is not such a life and death situation.

So?  Does that fact mean that a clearly worded statement is always a clear
indication?

> Does
> "indication" in R1483
> refer only to the words themselves or to the entire message in which the
> words are written?

It refers to an indication.  Merely posting the 'collection of text' with no
additional wording could be an indication of making a proposal (and I think
you will find that it has been treated as such.  Thus we preface draft
proposals with the word Pro-Proposal else they would count as Proposals).
There is no requirement to actually say "The following is a proposal" or
something similar.  Yes, Steve did include words to that effect but did they
clearly indicate the intent?

The words themselves are merely a part of the context of the message which
helps to make the indication of the purpose of the "collection of text"
clear.  They are not the indication but merely part of what makes it clear.
It is the context in which the "collection of text is deliver(ed)" that is
the indication.  We should feel free to examine as much of that context as
is necessary to determine whether the indication passes the test of clarity.

In this case I think it fails that test.

> The problem here is that you could easily substitute
> the words "clear wording" for "the clear indication" into R1483.  So while
> I recognize that there *can* be more to a clear indication than clear
> wording, I'm still not convinced that there is more to it in this
> particular
> case.
>

I submit you cannot make such a substitution.

-Macross


